  <exercise xml:id="ez-8a-3-1">
    <statement>
      <p>
        In <xref ref="eq-8a-3-infinite-geometric-sum">Equation</xref>, we learned that for an infinite geometric series
        <me>
          S = a + ar + ar^n + \cdots + ar^{n-1} + \cdots
        </me>,
        if <m>|r| \lt 1</m>, then 
        <me>
          S = \frac{a}{1-r}
        </me>.
        This result provides a quick way to determine the value of an infinite geometric series that converges.
      </p>

      <p>
        In this exercise, we explore why the infinite geometric series fails to converge when <m>r = 1</m>, <m>r = -1</m>, and <m>|r|>1</m>.
      </p>

      <p>
        <ol  marker="a.">
          <li>
            <p>
              If we consider the finite geometric series that results when <m>a = 1</m> and <m>r = 1</m>, we get the sum
              <me>
                S_n = 1 + 1 + \cdots + 1
              </me>,
              where there are <m>n</m> terms in the sum.
            </p>
            <ol marker="i.">
              <li>
                <p>
                  Compute <m>S_2</m>, <m>S_3</m>, and <m>S_4</m>.  What is the general formula for <m>S_n</m>?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Explain why the sequence <m>S_n</m> does not converge to a finite value.  Contrast this with, for example, our work in <xref ref="Ex-8a-3-inf-geom-1">Example</xref>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Next, consider the finite geometric series that results when <m>a = 1</m> and <m>r = -1</m>, which is the sum
              <me>
                S_n = 1 - 1 + 1 - 1 + \cdots + (-1)^{n-1}
              </me>,
              where there are <m>n</m> terms in the sum.  (We view the first <q><m>1</m></q> as resulting from <q><m>1 \cdot (-1)^0</m></q>.)
            </p>
            <ol marker="i.">
              <li>
                <p>
                  Compute <m>S_2</m>, <m>S_3</m>, <m>S_4</m>, and <m>S_5</m>.  What do you observe?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Explain why the sequence <m>S_n</m> does not converge to a finite value.  Contrast this with, for example, our work in <xref ref="Ex-8a-3-inf-geom-1">Example</xref>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>  
          </li>  
          <li>
              <p>
                Now consider the geometric sum with <m>a = 1</m> and <m>r = 2</m>, so 
                <me>
                  S_n = 1 + 2 + 4 + \cdots + 2^{n-1}
                </me>.
              </p>
              <ol marker="i.">
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Compute <m>S_2</m>, <m>S_3</m>, and <m>S_4</m>.  What is the general formula for <m>S_n</m>?
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    What do you observe happens to these partial sums as <m>n</m> increases without bound?  What does this tell us about the infinite geometric series <m>1 + 2 + 4 + \cdots + 2^{n-1} + \cdots</m>?
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>         
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
    
    <answer>
 
      <p>
        <ol  marker="a.">
          <li>
            <p>
              For 
              <m>
                S_n = 1 + 1 + \cdots + 1
              </m>,
            </p>
            <ol marker="i.">
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>S_2 = 1 + 1 = 2</m>, <m>S_3 = 1 + 1 + 1 = 3</m>, <m>S_4 = 4</m>, and <m>S_n = n</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  The infinite sum <m>S = 1 + 1 + \cdots + 1 + \cdots</m>  diverges.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              For
              <m>
                S_n = 1 - 1 + 1 - 1 + \cdots + (-1)^{n-1}
              </m>,
            </p>
            <ol marker="i.">
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>S_2 = 1 - 1 = 0</m>, <m>S_3 = 1 - 1 + 1 = 1</m>, <m>S_4 = 1 - 1 + 1 - 1 = 0</m>, <m>S_5 = 1 - 1 + 1 - 1 + 1 = 1</m>, and <m>S_n = 0</m> when <m>n</m> is even, and <m>S_n = 1</m> when <m>n</m> is odd.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  The infinite sum <m>S = 1 - 1 + 1 - 1 + \cdots + 1 - 1 + \cdots</m> diverges.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>  
          </li>  
          <li>
              <p>
                For 
                <m>
                  S_n = 1 + 2 + 4 + \cdots + 2^{n-1}
                </m>.
              </p>
              <ol marker="i.">
                <li>
                  <p>
                    <m>S_2 = \frac{1-2^2}{-1} = 3</m>, <m>S_3 = \frac{1-2^3}{-1} = 7</m>, and <m>S_4 = \frac{1-2^4}{-1} = 15</m>, so <m>S_n = 2^n - 1</m>.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    The infinite geometric series <m>1 + 2 + 4 + \cdots + 2^{n-1} + \cdots</m> diverges.
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>         
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>

    </answer>
    
    <solution>

      <p>
        <ol  marker="a.">
          <li>
            <p>
              We consider the finite geometric series that results when <m>a = 1</m> and <m>r = 1</m>:
              <me>
                S_n = 1 + 1 + \cdots + 1
              </me>,
              which has <m>n</m> terms in the sum.
            </p>
            <ol marker="i.">
              <li>
                <p>
                  Using 
                  <me>
                    S_n = 1 + 1 + \cdots + 1
                  </me>, 
                  we see that <m>S_2 = 1 + 1 = 2</m>, <m>S_3 = 1 + 1 + 1 = 3</m>, <m>S_4 = 4</m>, and more generally, <m>S_n = n</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Because the sequence <m>1, 2, 3, 4, \ldots, n, \ldots</m> increases without bound, partial sums of the series never approach a single finite value, so the sequence diverges, which means the infinite sum <m>S = 1 + 1 + \cdots + 1 + \cdots</m> also diverges.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Next, we consider the finite geometric series that results when <m>a = 1</m> and <m>r = -1</m>:
              <me>
                S_n = 1 - 1 + 1 - 1 + \cdots + (-1)^{n-1}
              </me>,
              which has <m>n</m> terms in the sum.  
            </p>
            <ol marker="i.">
              <li>
                <p>
                  Using <m>S_n = 1 - 1 + 1 - 1 + \cdots + (-1)^{n-1}</m>, we see that <m>S_2 = 1 - 1 = 0</m>, <m>S_3 = 1 - 1 + 1 = 1</m>, <m>S_4 = 1 - 1 + 1 - 1 = 0</m>, and <m>S_5 = 1 - 1 + 1 - 1 + 1 = 1</m>, and thus that <m>S_n = 0</m> when <m>n</m> is even, and <m>S_n = 1</m> when <m>n</m> is odd.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Because the sequence <m>1, 0, 1, 0, 1, 0, \ldots, 1, 0, \ldots</m> alterates between the values <m>0</m> and <m>1</m> partial sums of the series never approach a single finite value, so the sequence diverges, which means the infinite sum <m>S = 1 - 1 + 1 - 1 + \cdots + 1 - 1 + \cdots</m> also diverges.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>  
          </li>  
          <li>
              <p>
                Finally, we consider the geometric sum with <m>a = 1</m> and <m>r = 2</m>: 
                <me>
                  S_n = 1 + 2 + 4 + \cdots + 2^{n-1}
                </me>.
              </p>
              <ol marker="i.">
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Using the formula <m>S_n = \frac{a - ar^n}{1-4}</m>, we see that <m>S_2 = \frac{1-2^2}{-1} = 3</m>, <m>S_3 = \frac{1-2^3}{-1} = 7</m>, and <m>S_4 = \frac{1-2^4}{-1} = 15</m>, so <m>S_n = 2^n - 1</m>.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    The partial sums <m>S_n = 2^n - 1</m> increase without bound, so the infinite geometric series <m>1 + 2 + 4 + \cdots + 2^{n-1} + \cdots</m> diverges.
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>         
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
      
    </solution>
  </exercise>

